                    <h2>About The Piece</h2>
                    <p><em>“How to Be a Balloon Twister”</em> is a typographic book cover designed to visually represent a chosen profession using the elements and principles of design. The assignment required building a composition within a 3x3 grid system, focusing on one key letterform and abstract visual structure.</p>

                    <p>For this design, I explored the playful yet methodical world of balloon twisting. The cover references vintage how-to manuals and instructional graphics, reimagined through bold geometric shapes and implied forms. The overlapping curves mimic the inflated twists of balloon animals, while line patterns convey lightness, air, and translucent volume.</p>

                    <p>Directional arrows guide the eye across the page, echoing the step-by-step logic of DIY guides. Cropped and fragmented shapes build tension across the asymmetrical grid while leading to the implied “B” in the bottom right corner—the first letter of the profession and the composition’s payoff.</p>

                    <p><em>“How to Be a Balloon Twister”</em> is an exercise in clarity, movement, and playful precision, transforming simple visual elements into a coded language of instruction and form.</p>

